<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<job id="employee-documents-retention" xmlns="http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee" version="1.0">
    <!--
    Employee Documents Retention Job (S3-only employee documents, spec §6.10)

    Purpose:
    The employee half of "GDPR runs itself": hard-delete every stored
    document (all S3 object versions + rows) of ex-employees whose latest
    status is TERMINATED and whose termination date is more than
    employee_documents.retention.years (default 5, decision D4) years ago.
    Per-user RETENTION_DELETE audit rows + one run-summary row snapshotting
    the policy in force. At most retention.nightly-user-cap users per run.

    Armed at runtime by the employee_documents.retention.enabled app
    setting (seeded OFF by V452) - ENABLING THAT SETTING ON THE SETTINGS
    TAB IS THE MOMENT AUTOMATIC DELETION STARTS. While unarmed the job is
    a cheap no-op, so shipping it dark is safe.

    Idempotency: an erased user has no employee_documents rows left and is
    never selected again; S3 deletes are idempotent. Re-runs and draining-
    task double-runs are harmless.

    Schedule:
    Daily at 02:10 UTC via BatchScheduler (the slot the retired
    s3-retention-cleanup reaper used), gated by
    dk.trustworks.employee-documents.retention-job.enabled (default true).

    Similar to:
    recruitment-gdpr-sweep.xml (the candidate-side GDPR clock)
    -->

    <listeners>
        <listener ref="jobMonitoringListener"/>
    </listeners>

    <step id="sweep-employee-documents-retention">
        <listeners>
            <listener ref="stepProgressListener"/>
        </listeners>

        <batchlet ref="employeeDocumentsRetentionBatchlet"/>
    </step>
</job>
